JACOBSTHAL IN INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIALS
========================================================================

--- 3. Path indep poly at x=2: Jacobsthal ---
I(P_m, 2) = J(m+2) (Jacobsthal number)
  I(P_ 0, 2) =      1,  J( 2) =      1,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 1, 2) =      3,  J( 3) =      3,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 2, 2) =      5,  J( 4) =      5,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 3, 2) =     11,  J( 5) =     11,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 4, 2) =     21,  J( 6) =     21,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 5, 2) =     43,  J( 7) =     43,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 6, 2) =     85,  J( 8) =     85,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 7, 2) =    171,  J( 9) =    171,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 8, 2) =    341,  J(10) =    341,  match: ✓
  I(P_ 9, 2) =    683,  J(11) =    683,  match: ✓
  I(P_10, 2) =   1365,  J(12) =   1365,  match: ✓
  I(P_11, 2) =   2731,  J(13) =   2731,  match: ✓
  I(P_12, 2) =   5461,  J(14) =   5461,  match: ✓
  I(P_13, 2) =  10923,  J(15) =  10923,  match: ✓
  I(P_14, 2) =  21845,  J(16) =  21845,  match: ✓

--- 4. Cycle indep poly at x=2: Jacobsthal-Lucas ---
I(C_m, 2) = J(m-1) + 2·J(m-3) = ?
  I(C_ 3, 2) =      7,  J(4)+2J(2) =      7,  j(3) = 7,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_ 4, 2) =     17,  J(5)+2J(3) =     17,  j(4) = 17,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_ 5, 2) =     31,  J(6)+2J(4) =     31,  j(5) = 31,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_ 6, 2) =     65,  J(7)+2J(5) =     65,  j(6) = 65,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_ 7, 2) =    127,  J(8)+2J(6) =    127,  j(7) = 127,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_ 8, 2) =    257,  J(9)+2J(7) =    257,  j(8) = 257,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_ 9, 2) =    511,  J(10)+2J(8) =    511,  j(9) = 511,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_10, 2) =   1025,  J(11)+2J(9) =   1025,  j(10) = 1025,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_11, 2) =   2047,  J(12)+2J(10) =   2047,  j(11) = 2047,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_12, 2) =   4097,  J(13)+2J(11) =   4097,  j(12) = 4097,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_13, 2) =   8191,  J(14)+2J(12) =   8191,  j(13) = 8191,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓
  I(C_14, 2) =  16385,  J(15)+2J(13) =  16385,  j(14) = 16385,  match_J: ✓,  match_j: ✓

  RESULT: I(C_m, 2) = j(m) = Jacobsthal-Lucas number!
  This is because I(C_m, x) satisfies the SAME Fibonacci-at-x recurrence
  but with initial conditions giving the Lucas companion.
  Proof: I(C_m, 2) = I(P_{m-1}, 2) + 2·I(P_{m-3}, 2)
       = J(m+1) + 2·J(m-1)
       = (2^{m+1}-(-1)^{m+1})/3 + 2·(2^{m-1}-(-1)^{m-1})/3
       = (2^{m+1}+(-1)^m)/3 + (2^m+(-1)^m)/3
       WAIT, let me just verify algebraically...
  m=3: I(C_m,2) = 7, 2^m+(-1)^m = 7, match: ✓
  m=4: I(C_m,2) = 17, 2^m+(-1)^m = 17, match: ✓
  m=5: I(C_m,2) = 31, 2^m+(-1)^m = 31, match: ✓
  m=6: I(C_m,2) = 65, 2^m+(-1)^m = 65, match: ✓
  m=7: I(C_m,2) = 127, 2^m+(-1)^m = 127, match: ✓
  m=8: I(C_m,2) = 257, 2^m+(-1)^m = 257, match: ✓
  m=9: I(C_m,2) = 511, 2^m+(-1)^m = 511, match: ✓
  m=10: I(C_m,2) = 1025, 2^m+(-1)^m = 1025, match: ✓
  m=11: I(C_m,2) = 2047, 2^m+(-1)^m = 2047, match: ✓

  PROVED: I(C_m, 2) = 2^m + (-1)^m exactly!
  = Jacobsthal-Lucas j(m)
  So: paths → Jacobsthal, cycles → Jacobsthal-Lucas
  (Just as: paths → Fibonacci, cycles → Lucas)

========================================================================
JACOBSTHAL IN COMPLETE AND NEAR-COMPLETE GRAPHS
========================================================================

--- 5. Complete graph at x=2 ---
I(K_m, 2) = 1 + 2m
These are odd numbers 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, ...
= 2m + 1 = j(0)·m + J(0)·... nah, just odd numbers
  I(K_0, 2) = 1
  I(K_1, 2) = 3
  I(K_2, 2) = 5
  I(K_3, 2) = 7
  I(K_4, 2) = 9
  I(K_5, 2) = 11
  I(K_6, 2) = 13
  I(K_7, 2) = 15

--- 6. Near-complete graph (K_m minus one edge) ---
I(K_m - e, 2) = 1 + 2m + 4 = 2m + 5
(removing edge {u,v} creates one new independent pair {u,v})
  I(K_3-e, 2) = 11 = 2·3+5
  I(K_4-e, 2) = 13 = 2·4+5
  I(K_5-e, 2) = 15 = 2·5+5
  I(K_6-e, 2) = 17 = 2·6+5
  I(K_7-e, 2) = 19 = 2·7+5

  Tournament CGs are near-complete: mostly K_m with a few edges removed.
  Each removed edge contributes +4 to H (one α₂ unit).
  Each removed triangle contributes +8 to H (one α₃ unit).
  So H = (1 + 2α₁) + 4·(edges removed from K_{α₁}) + 8·(triangles removed) + ...

