--- 9. General k-Jacobsthal dominant roots ---
k-Jacobsthal: f(n) = f(n-1) + 2f(n-2) + ... + 2^{k-1}f(n-k)
Char poly: t^k = t^{k-1} + 2t^{k-2} + ... + 2^{k-1}

  k    dom root                  name  standard k-nacci     ratio
  2    2.000000            Jacobsthal          1.618034  1.236068
  3    2.467504       Trib-Jacobsthal          1.839287  1.341555
  4    2.698069      Tetra-Jacobsthal          1.927562  1.399731
  5    2.820830      Penta-Jacobsthal          1.965948  1.434844
  6    2.890197       Hexa-Jacobsthal          1.983583  1.457059
  7    2.931142      Hepta-Jacobsthal          1.991964  1.471484
  8    2.956097          8-Jacobsthal          1.996031  1.480988
  9    2.971669          9-Jacobsthal          1.998029  1.487300
 10    2.981555         10-Jacobsthal          1.999019  1.491510
 11    2.987914         11-Jacobsthal          1.999510  1.494323

Key observation:
  Standard k-nacci constants → 2
  k-Jacobsthal constants → 3
  Ratio → 3/2 = 1.5

  WHY 3? Because the char equation at x=2 is:
  t^k = t^{k-1} + 2t^{k-2} + ... + 2^{k-1}
  = t^{k-1}·(1 + 2/t + 4/t² + ... + 2^{k-1}/t^{k-1})
  = t^{k-1}·(1-(2/t)^k)/(1-2/t)  [geometric series]
  For large k: t^k ≈ t^{k-1}·t/(t-2)
  → t ≈ t/(t-2) → t² - 2t = t → t² = 3t → t = 3

