========================================================================
THE JACOBSTHAL MATRIX
========================================================================

The Jacobsthal recurrence J(n) = J(n-1) + 2·J(n-2) has companion matrix:
  M = [[1, 2],
       [1, 0]]

M^n = [[J(n+1), 2·J(n)],
       [J(n),   2·J(n-1)]]

det(M) = -2 (eigenvalues 2 and -1)

For tournament with adjacency A (skew: A+A^T = J-I):
  det(I + 2A) is always a perfect square (HYP-788)

Question: is there a Jacobsthal matrix hiding inside I + 2A?

Jacobsthal companion matrix M:
[[1 2]
 [1 0]]
det(M) = -2
eigenvalues: [ 2. -1.]

Powers of M:
  M^0 = [[1, 0], [0, 1]], J values: J(1)=1, J(0)=0
  M^1 = [[1, 2], [1, 0]], J values: J(2)=1, J(1)=1
  M^2 = [[3, 2], [1, 2]], J values: J(3)=3, J(2)=1
  M^3 = [[5, 6], [3, 2]], J values: J(4)=5, J(3)=3
  M^4 = [[11, 10], [5, 6]], J values: J(5)=11, J(4)=5
  M^5 = [[21, 22], [11, 10]], J values: J(6)=21, J(5)=11
  M^6 = [[43, 42], [21, 22]], J values: J(7)=43, J(6)=21
  M^7 = [[85, 86], [43, 42]], J values: J(8)=85, J(7)=43

--- 12. Connection to I+2A ---
For tournament T on n vertices, A = adjacency matrix (0/1)
S = A - A^T = skew-symmetric, S = 2A - (J-I)
I + 2A = I + S + (J-I) = S + J
       Wait: I + 2A where A is 0/1 upper, A^T is 0/1 lower
       A + A^T = J - I (all-ones minus identity)
       So 2A = (A+A^T) + (A-A^T) = (J-I) + S
       I + 2A = I + J - I + S = J + S
       where J is all-ones and S is skew-symmetric!

  det(I + 2A) = det(J + S)
  where J = all-ones matrix (rank 1)
  and S = A - A^T (skew-symmetric)

  J + S has a special structure: J is the rank-1 perturbation
  that breaks the skew-symmetry. det(J + S) is always a perfect square.

Verification at n=3:
  T=[0, 0, 0]: H=1, det(I+2A)=1, √=1, H²=1, det/H²=1.000
  T=[1, 0, 0]: H=1, det(I+2A)=1, √=1, H²=1, det/H²=1.000
  T=[0, 1, 0]: H=3, det(I+2A)=9, √=3, H²=9, det/H²=1.000
  T=[1, 1, 0]: H=1, det(I+2A)=1, √=1, H²=1, det/H²=1.000
  T=[0, 0, 1]: H=1, det(I+2A)=1, √=1, H²=1, det/H²=1.000
  T=[1, 0, 1]: H=3, det(I+2A)=9, √=3, H²=9, det/H²=1.000
  T=[0, 1, 1]: H=1, det(I+2A)=1, √=1, H²=1, det/H²=1.000
  T=[1, 1, 1]: H=1, det(I+2A)=1, √=1, H²=1, det/H²=1.000

Verification at n=4:
  H=  1: det(I+2A)=       1, √det=   1, √det/H=1.0000
  H=  3: det(I+2A)=       9, √det=   3, √det/H=1.0000
